<HL> GE's NBC News Defamed
Wayne Newton, Jury Finds</HL>
<DD> 12/18/86</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> GE
TELECOMMUNICATIONS, BROADCASTING, TELEPHONE, TELEGRAPH (TEL)
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS) </IN>
<DATELINE> LAS VEGAS, Nev.  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal jury found NBC News guilty of defaming entertainer Wayne Newton in a series of broadcasts that linked him to organized crime.

   After a two-month trial and a week of deliberations, the 10-member panel voted unanimously against NBC News, a division of General Electric Co.'s National Broadcasting Co. unit.
The jury awarded Mr. Newton $19.2 million in damages, including $5 million in punitive damages, $5 million for loss of reputation, $7.9 million for loss of income, $1.1 million for loss of future income and $225,000 for physical and mental suffering.

   NBC News said it will appeal the verdict.
Its lawyers had argued the broadcasts, in 1980 and 1981, were "substantially accurate."
In a statement, Lawrence K. Grossman, NBC News president, predicted the division and its reporters on the story "will prevail in a higher court."

   In the broadcasts, NBC News suggested that Mr. Newton had obtained financing to buy the Aladdin Hotel and Casino through links to organized crime and that he had sought help from organized-crime figures to end death threats against his family.
Mr. Newton contended the broadcast resulted in, among other things, the loss of millions of dollars in Las Vegas bookings and a movie contract.
He later sold his stake in the Aladdin to a business partner.

</TEXT>
