<HEAD>Federal Appeals Court Hears Arguments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC News urged a federal appeals court
Friday to reverse a $5.3 million libel judgment won by entertainer
Wayne Newton, saying a 1980 broadcast was guilty of only one thing
_ aggressive journalism.
   Newton's lawyer, Morton Galane, argued that a jury found NBC had
``ill will'' toward Newton and said the verdict should stand.
   But NBC lawyer Floyd Abrams said the report linking Newton to
organized crime figures was correct. Abrams, a noted First
Amendment lawyer, argued that investigative reporting would suffer
if the decision were upheld.
   The two lawyers spoke during 30-minute oral summations to their
arguments at the hearing before the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeal. The court's decision will be announced at a later date.
   A Las Vegas federal jury decided in December 1986 that the
network had willfully libeled Newton by claiming he had ties to
organized crime. The jury gave him the largest libel award in
history _ $19.2 million in damages.
   Presiding U.S. District Judge Myron Crocker of Fresno eventually
reduced that award to $5.3 million.
   Numerous media groups, including rival networks CBS, ABC and
Fox, several major newspaper chains and The Associated Press have
joined NBC's appeal of the libel verdict.
   During Friday's hearing, Judge William Norris of the
three-member panel likened the NBC team to Robert Woodward and Carl
Bernstein, the Washington Post reporters who broke the Watergate
scandal.
   ``Would a jury have a basis for finding Carl Bernstein and
Robert Woodward had ill will in pursuing the Watergate story?'' he
asked Newton's lawyer.
   Galane said they would not because those reporters were ordered
by their publisher to verify every fact through at least two
sources.
   But Norris suggested the Newton case might discourage
investigative reporting and prevent stories comparable to a
Watergate scandal from being uncovered.
   ``We tread a very fine line here to make sure that future
Woodwards and Bernsteins are not inhibited in pursuing their
stories,'' said Norris.
   Galane responded, ``We are not intending to inhibit such
goals,'' and declared at one point: ``We're not here to launch an
attack on the media or the First Amendment.''
   But he maintained that NBC had erred by not interviewing Newton
about its allegations.
   Abrams countered that Newton had refused numerous requests for
such an interview.
   Newton, who listened to the arguments from a front row seat,
later told reporters he still feels the impact of the 1980
broadcast that linked him to reputed mob figure Guido Penosi.
   ``The effects of what they said will last me the rest of my
life,'' he said.
   NBC reporter Brian Ross said he and his co-defendants, producer
Ira Silverman and executive producer Paul Greenberg, were ``very
optimistic'' about having the verdict overturned. All three
attended the hearing.
   The case began Oct. 6, 1980, with Ross' report ``Wayne Newton
and the Law.'' Ross reported that Newton had gone to Penosi for
help with a problem and that unnamed federal sources were looking
at Newton's relationship to two East Coast crime figures.
   The reports said one mobster had bragged of earning an interest
in Las Vegas' Aladdin Hotel, which Newton owned at the time.
   Newton claimed the report left the impression that his October
1980 purchase of the Aladdin was tied to organized crime _ which he
denies. Newton later sold the hotel.
   Abrams told reporters outside court: ``I think that a loss in
this case would make it very difficult for the press to report
about investigations and suspicions about prominent public figures,
particularly in their own community.''
   Judge Dorothy Nelson and chief appellate Judge Alfred Goodwin
joined Norris on the panel. Nelson expressed interest in an NBC
argument that the case should have been moved out of Las Vegas.
   Abrams said the defense submitted data on ``Mr. Newton's general
adulation in Las Vegas'' but was unable to win a change of venue.
   ``It was nearly hopeless for us to get a fair trial in Las
Vegas,'' he said.
</TEXT>
