<TEXT>
   Nearly two years after a jury awarded a $19.2 million libel verdict to entertainer Wayne Newton, his case against National Broadcasting Co. is heading to trial -- again.

   Court papers filed last week in U.S. district court in Los Angeles disclosed that Mr. Newton's attorneys will seek to limit the second trial to a question of how much Mr. Newton was damaged by an NBC broadcast, while the network's lawyers will try to reopen broader issues raised in the first trial.
NBC is a unit of General Electric Co. of Fairfield, Conn.

   The case concerns an Oct. 6, 1980, NBC news broadcast entitled "Wayne Newton and the Law."
In the segment, NBC reported that Mr. Newton had gone to Guido Penosi, who reputedly had ties to organized crime, for help with a problem, which wasn't named.

   Two days before the broadcast aired, Mr. Newton bought a half-ownership in the Aladdin Hotel in Las Vegas, Nev.
He argued that the NBC report created the impression that he had received financial assistance from organized-crime figures to finance the purchase.

   At trial, Mr. Newton testified he sought Mr. Penosi's assistance after receiving death threats against his daughter.
Mr. Newton also said he received a bank loan to finance the purchase of the hotel, a fact not mentioned in the broadcast.

   In December 1986, after two months of testimony, the jury awarded Mr. Newton $19.2 million in damages, the largest libel award ever against a news organization.
But U.S. District Judge Myron Crocker reduced the award to $5.3 million, setting aside the jury's award for loss of income and reducing an award for injury to reputation from $5 million to $50,000.

   In an unusual move, Mr. Newton rejected Judge Crocker's reduced award and sought a new trial on damages only.
"Mr.
Newton felt that in light of his reputation the award for reputational injury should have been higher," said Morton Galane of Las Vegas, Mr. Newton's lawyer.

   In a legal brief, Mr. Galane argued that he should be allowed to introduce new evidence on Mr. Newton's loss of income in order for the jury to assess damages properly.
He is also seeking punitive damages against the network, alleging that statements made by NBC executives following the trial demonstrate continued ill will toward Mr. Newton, the court papers said.

   Punitive damages are aimed at punishing the defendant rather than compensating the injured party.
NBC argues that such damages are unconstitutional in First Amendment cases.

   NBC is seeking to present a broad range of evidence to show that it didn't broadcast false statements that damaged Mr. Newton, according to Floyd Abrams of the New York law firm of Cahill Gordon &amp; Reindel, representing the network.
Mr. Newton's lawyers have argued that it is enough that the broadcast created a false impression, even if each statement taken separately was true.

   Judge Crocker is expected to hear oral arguments on the scope of the new trial on Nov. 15.
The trial isn't expected to begin until May 1989.

</TEXT>
</DOC>

