<HEAD>Audio, Video Equipment Banned at Neil Bush Hearing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators say audio and video recording
equipment won't be allowed at the Sept. 25 public hearing on Neil
Bush's role in the failure of Silverado Banking savings and loan.
   Bush, who faces charges that he acted improperly as a director
of Silverado, was scheduled to testify. He was an outside director
of Silverado from 1985 until shortly before the thrift was seized
by regulators in 1988.
   Bush has been accused of conflicts of interest in his dealings
with former developers Ken Good and Bill Walters, two major
Silverado borrowers.
   The decision not to allow recording equipment angered Rep. Pat
Schroeder, D-Colo., and the Colorado Broadcasters Association.
   Dan Buck, an administrative assistant to Schroeder, said he
understood the federal Office of Thrift Supervision wanting to
avoid turning the hearing into a circus. ``But the taxpayers have
already bought $1 billion worth of ducats to the Silverado failure,
and they should be able to see the investigative process,'' he
said.
   Past administrative hearings have been closed to the public
entirely. In July, because of interest in the national savings and
loan fiasco, the policy was changed, but recording devices still
are not permitted at Office of Thrift Supervision hearings.
   The broadcasters' association sent a letter to the agency's
director, Timothy Ryan, requesting at least one television camera
inside the Neil Bush hearing.
   The association also asked Ryan to move the hearing from
Denver's federal courthouse building, where video equipment never
is permitted. He suggested other hearing sites that allow cameras,
including the University of Denver and state and county courtrooms.
   ``The broadcast media makes a judgment in terms of what they
believe the public is most interested in,'' said Andrew Low, an
attorney for the association and KUSA-TV in Denver.
   ``It is beyond question that Neil Bush's involvement in the
failure of Silverado is of considerable public interest,
particularly in Colorado where Neil Bush lives,'' Low said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FCC Chairman Says Budget Hearings May Delay Cable Bill Vote</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation to re-regulate the cable television
industry may not get a final vote by Congress this year, the
chairman of the Federal Communications Commission told broadcasters
Sept. 18.
   Alfred C. Sikes said the continuing House-Senate negotiations on
the federal budget could cause the delay. The House has passed a
cable bill but a vote on a similar measure in the Senate still is
pending.
   He made the remarks in responding to questions posed at a lunch
held by the International Radio and Television Society in New York.
   Only a month ago, Sikes said, he would have said he felt ``there
was a substantial likelihood'' of a final vote by both houses this
year.
   But now, ``I think that in some ways the fate of the cable
legislation is tied to (federal) budget negotiations,'' he said.
   As the talks drag on and if negotiators ``tighten the rules on
floor action in Congress, it would seem to me that the cable
legislation will run out of time'' for a final vote before the
current session of Congress ends, he said.
   The Bush administration strongly opposes the House bill, saying
Congress should instead encourage new forms of competition to
cable. That industry was largely freed of regulation by Congress in
1984.
   Among other things, the House measure, passed in response to
increasing complaints about overpricing and shoddy cable TV
service, would impose federal price limits on basic cable service.
   It also would give the FCC power to order price rollbacks on the
worst offenders and boost competition to cable, which now serves
58.9 percent of the nation's 93.1 million homes with TV, according
to Nielsen estimates.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Newton Will Appeal NBC Libel Ruling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wayne Newton asked a federal appeals court to
reconsider a ruling that overturned his record $5.2 million libel
judgment against NBC News for a 1980 broadcast linking him to
organized crime.
   Lawyers for Newton said the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
``overlooked or misconstrued'' some evidence and interpreted other
evidence unfairly in favor of NBC in its Aug. 30 ruling.
   In a petition asking for a rehearing, the attorneys said that
failing to overturn the verdict would ``chill the rights of public
figures to bring defamation suits against powerful media
defendants.''
   Newton attorney Morton Galane said Sept. 20 that he filed the
petition.
   A jury in Las Vegas found that NBC's story falsely implied that
organized crime figures had helped Newton buy the Aladdin Hotel and
Casino in exchange for a hidden interest.
   It awarded Newton $19.3 million, but that was later reduced to
$5.2 million, mostly in punitive damages
</TEXT>
