<HL>
   Enterprise:
   Shakeout Helps Makers of Wood Stoves
   ---
   Boom Shows How Industry's Woes
   Can Have Silver Lining
   ----
   By Eugene Carlson
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
01/16/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2
</SO>
<IN>
HOME ELECTRONICS, FURNISHINGS, APPLIANCES (HMF)
CORPORATE PROFILE (PRO)
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
</IN>
<GV>
ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY (EPA)
</GV>
<LP>
   COLVILLE, Wash. -- Sales are booming at Aladdin Steel
Products Inc., largely because of two unlikely forces: the
Environmental Protection Agency and Saddam Hussein.
   Aladdin makes wood-burning stoves here in this remote
corner of northeast Washington state. It emerged from an
industry shakeout that killed off all but about three dozen
of the 300 or so U.S. companies that were making wood stoves
a decade ago. Aladdin and the other survivors are now
profiting from a renewed infatuation with wood as an energy
source. Their present prosperity also shows how an industry's
disaster can sometimes be turned to a company's advantage.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Wood-stove sales in the U.S. last year ran close to
270,000 units, estimates the Wood Heating Alliance, a
Washington, D.C.-based trade group. While that's a far cry
from the more than one-million-unit-sales years of a decade
ago, it's up about 20% from a year before.
   The industry's current prosperity partly reflects the
latest unpredictable turn in the topsy-turvy world of energy
economics. The 1990 run-up in world oil prices following
Iraq's invasion of Kuwait last August sparked the concern of
homeowners about rising prices for home heating oil. And in
the fall, overall wood-stove sales took off for the first
time in nearly 10 years.
   Iraq's invasion "unquestionably juiced the market rather
dramatically," says Jack Hughes, chief executive of Vermont
Castings Inc., Randolph, Vt., a large wood-stove maker. Adds
Aladdin's co-owner and vice president Daniel Henry about
Saddam Hussein: "He didn't hurt our industry."
   Sales of Aladdin's Quadra-Fire model stoves reached $5.2
million in 1990, up from $3.2 million the previous year. The
11-year-old company has expanded far beyond its Pacific
Northwest base, shipping stoves to dealers in 42 states. And
notwithstanding the recession, Mr. Henry sees no sign of a
slowdown. "We normally cut back our manufacturing this time
of year, but we're still back ordered, so we're running wide
open," he says.
   But the Middle East crisis isn't the only reason for
Aladdin's success. Aladdin survived an onslaught of rules and
restrictions aimed at wood-stove makers that eventually
crushed a majority of the firms.
   Concerned about noxious wood smoke pollution that shrouded
cities such as Denver; Medford, Ore.; and Missoula, Mont.,
during winter months, state environmental departments in the
mid-1980s began drafting emission standards for wood stoves,
not unlike those required of cars. The EPA made the crackdown
nationwide in 1986. This forced stove makers to develop
ingenious ways to reduce pollution, such as fitting
stovepipes with catalytic converters.
   Wood stoves produced in the late 1970s typically produced
40 to 60 grams of particulate matter an hour. The EPA set an
allowable level of only 4.1 grams an hour for stoves
manufactured after July 1, 1990, that were fitted with
catalytic combustion devices. Stoves without catalytic
devices, favored by Aladdin, are allowed an emission ceiling
of 7.5 grams an hour.
   The EPA regulations effectively wiped out scores of small
stove makers that couldn't bear the cost of redesigning their
stoves to meet the clean air standards.
   "You're looking at $100,000 plus" in design costs and
certification fees, says Ben Myren, a partner at Energy &amp;
Environmental Measurement Corp., a Kent, Wash., laboratory
that tests stoves for the EPA. "It used to be that anyone who
was a welder could build a stove, but it's not a backyard
industry anymore." Adds Mr. Hughes of Vermont Castings,
"You're dealing with survival of the fittest."
   For Aladdin, the air quality crackdown proved a blessing
in disguise. The company was young, without a big investment
in inefficient designs. At a 1984 Oregon trade show, Alan
Trusler, Aladdin's 35-year-old president, recalls that he and
Mr. Henry caught hints of an emerging Oregon wood-stove
emission standard. "We came back, looked at each other, and
said `It's time to get in or get out.' We decided to get in."
   While a lot of manufacturers tried unsuccessfully to
jury-rig their existing models to meet the new air quality
standards, Aladdin chose to scrap its small line of
traditional stoves and develop a new model from scratch. It
took nearly two years of mechanical engineering "and a lot of
sitting in front of the fire," to come up with a
clean-burning design, Mr. Trusler says.
   Adds Mr. Henry: "Tuning a stove is like tuning a car
engine. It's an air-to-fuel problem."
   The two men moved to tiny Colville from Southern
California in 1979, looking for a pleasant rural environment.
Mr. Trusler had a business background. Mr. Henry, now 38, was
a skilled mechanic. "He taught me how to weld," Mr. Trusler
says of his partner, "and I taught him to say `no' to bad
debt."
   Today, a two-shift work force of 72 employees uses $1
million of computer-guided steel plate stamping and cutting
machines to produce 60 firewood-fueled stoves a day. The
plant turns out another 10 to 15 "pellet" stoves a day, an
increasingly popular type of stove that uses tiny pellets of
compressed wood waste as fuel. Mr. Trusler says Aladdin will
sell close to 10,500 stoves of both types in the 12 months
ending March 31 vs. 6,300 a year earlier.
   Aladdin's Quadra-Fire 3100 model was the lowest polluting
noncatalytic stove among 63 models rated by the EPA last
October. It retails for about $1,000. Vermont Castings'
Defiant Encore, at $1,450, was the cleanest burning model
among 85 catalytic stoves tested. The lowest emissions for
seven pellet-fuel stoves was the Venturi PVI-87 made by
Martin Industries Inc., Florence, Ala.
</TEXT>
