<HL> Judge Throws Out Most
Of Newton Libel Judgment</HL>
<DD> 11/19/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> GE </IN>
<DATELINE> LAS VEGAS, Nev. (AP)  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge yesterday threw out all but $5.3 million of the record $22.8 million libel judgment won by Wayne Newton against National Broadcasting Co. for news stories linking the singer to organized crime figures.

   U.S. District Judge Myron Crocker, in upholding the liability portion of the jury award, ruled that Mr. Newton had proved by "clear and convincing evidence" that NBC had defamed him.

   But the judge cut nearly $17.5 million awarded for damage to Mr. Newton's reputation and loss of earnings.
He said the evidence didn't support Mr. Newton's allegation that the broadcasts hurt his reputation or cut his earnings.

   New York-based NBC is a unit of General Electric Co. NBC attorney Floyd Abrams said the network will continue to appeal the verdict.

   "We are pleased the damages have been significantly reduced but still believe they are far beyond any amount that could possibly be sustained," he said.
"It still is a loss in the sense that the judge is assuring the jury verdict of liability."

   "It's a big victory for Wayne Newton," said Mr. Newton's attorney Morton Galane.
"It vindicates him completely, and it's still the biggest libel award in history."

   Mr. Galane said Mr. Newton hasn't decided whether to accept the reduced damages or seek a new trial on damages only.

